500'. Quos rami fructus, &c.] No man's memory has been more tra- duced than that of Epicurus. He has been represented as a person wholly given up to luxury and intem- perance. His name is become a proverb, to expressa voluptuous per- son, whose whole pleasure was in eating and drinking. And yet it is certain that he was a great pattern of temperance, and recommended it to his followerS. Diogenes Laertius informs us that he was contented with bread and water, and, when he had a mind to gratisy his appetite, he added a piece of cheese.
